                <h2>Treatment Techniques</h2>
                <p class="lead">The breast cancer can be treated by various treatment techniques depending on the stage of the cancer. <br /> </p>
                <p class="lead"><b><h3>Prescription</h3></b></p>
                <p class="lead"><b>Hormones: </b> Tamoxifen (Soltamox) </p>
                <p class="lead"><b>Other treatments: </b> Exemestane (Aromasin), Docetaxel by injection (Docefrez), Capecitabine (Xeloda), Letrozole (Femara), Cyclophosphamide by injection, Anastrozole (Arimidex), Paclitaxel by injection (Taxol), Zoledronic acid by injection (Zometa), Trastuzumab by injection, Epirubicin by injection (Ellence) </p>
                <p class="lead"><b><h3>Also common </h3></b></p>
                <p class="lead"><b>Chemotherapy regimen:</b> AC regimen, FEC regimen, Doxorubicin-Docetaxel regimen, TCH regimen, AC-T regimen, TAC regimen </p>
                <p class="lead"><b>Procedures:</b> Lumpectomy, Radiation therapy, Breast surgery, Radical mastectomy, Mastectomy, Wide local excision, External beam radiotherapy, Mammaplasty, Tissue expansion, Neoadjuvant therapy, Breast-Conserving surgery, Lymphadenectomy </p>
                <p class="lead"><b>Other treatments: </b> Hormone therapy </p>
                <p class="lead"><b><h3>Specialists </h3></b></p>
                <p class="lead"><b>Oncologist:</b> Specializes in cancer</p>
                <p class="lead"><b>Radiologist: </b> Uses images to diagnose and treat disease within the body. </p>
                <p class="lead"><b>Radiation oncologist: </b> Treats and manages cancer by prescribing radiation therapy.</p>
                <p class="lead"><b>Plastic surgeon: </b> Reconstructs defective, damaged, or missing body parts. </p>
                <p class="lead"><b>Surgeon: </b> Performs operations to treat disease. </p> <br> <br> <br> <br>
